<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-141-082 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 113 045</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Software Engineering  June 1991 v17 n6p582(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why is software late? An empirical study of reasons for delay insoftware development. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>van Genuchten, Michiel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study done in 1988 and 1989 in a software engineering departmenton the difference between the planned and actual progress of asoftware project showed the major reasons for delay were more timespent on other work than planned and underestimating thecomplexity of applications.andP;  Investigation showed that maintenanceactivities were the primary cause of interrupted development.andP;  Thesurvey also showed that external entities influence the executionof a project plan; sometimes planned resources are not providedand sometimes the marketing department does not deliver clearlydefined requirements on time.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software EngineeringProgrammingBusiness PlanningProject ManagementSoftware MaintenanceSurveyMeasurement.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Distribution of relative effort overruns. (graph)Distribution of relative schedule overruns. (graph)Prevalence of cost overruns. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>